<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="secA1-MidtermReview" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Midterm Review</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>
            The midterm exam will cover material from Week 1 Day 1 of the class through Week 3 Day 2. 
            That is, it covers material in the following sections: 
            <ul marker="">
                <li>
                    <xref ref="sec11-SystemLinearEquations"/> Systems of Linear Equations
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <xref ref="sec12-RowReduction"/> Row Reduction and Echelon Forms
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <xref ref="sec13-VectorEquations"/> Vector Equations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <xref ref="sec14-MatrixEquation"/> The Matrix Equation <m>A\v{x} = \v{b}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <xref ref="sec15-SolutionSets"/> Solution Sets of Linear Systems
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <xref ref="sec17-LinearIndependence"/> Linear Independence
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <xref ref="sec18-IntroLinearTransformations"/> Introduction to Linear Transformations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <xref ref="sec19-MatrixLinearTransformation"/> The Matrix of a Linear Transformation
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <xref ref="sec21-MatrixOperations"/> Matrix Operations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <xref ref="sec22-InverseMatrix"/> The Inverse of a Matrix
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <xref ref="sec23-InvertibleMatrix"/> Characterizations of Invertible Matrices
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
            On this page, you will find review problems for the midterm exam. 
            The final answers are included for each problem.
            Make sure you spend some time working through these problems and understanding how things work! 
        </p>

        <p>
            <alert>A quick reminder:</alert> Some class time during the class session before the midterm exam will be a review session. 
            Usually this will be a work day for you to work through some problems together to prepare for the exam. 
            This is also a great opportunity for you to ask questions about anything that is not clear to you! 
        </p>
    </introduction>

    <worksheet xml:id="ws-MidtermReview-SystemEquations">
        <title>Systems of Linear Equations</title>
        
        <exercise>
            <p>
                Solve the following system of equations: 
                <md>
                    \begin{cases}
                        x_1 + 3x_2 - 5x_3 + x_4 = 4 \\
                        2x_1 + 5x_2 - 2x_3 + 4x_4 = 6 \\
                    \end{cases}
                </md>
                If the system is consistent, write the solution set as a column vector 
                If the system is inconsistent, explain how you know it.
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    The solutions are of the form 
                    <m>
                        \begin{bmatrix} -2 - 19s - 7t \\ 2 + 8s + 2t \\ s \\ t \end{bmatrix}
                    </m>
                    where <m>s</m> and <m>t</m> are arbitrary constants.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Solve the following system of linear equations: 
                <md>
                    <mrow>x_2 + 4x_3 \amp = -4</mrow>
                    <mrow>x_1 + 3x_2 + 3x_3 \amp = -2</mrow>
                    <mrow>3x_1 + 7x_2 + 5x_3 \amp = 6</mrow>
                </md>
                If the system is consistent, write the solution set as a column vector 
                If the system is inconsistent, explain how you know it.
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    The solution is <m>\begin{bmatrix} 19 \\ -8 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Solve the following system of linear equations:
                <md>
                    <mrow>x_1 - 3x_3 \amp = 8</mrow>
                    <mrow>2x_1 + 2x_2 + 9x_3 \amp = 7</mrow>
                    <mrow>x_2 + 5x_3 \amp = -2</mrow>
                </md>
                If the system is consistent, write the solution set as a column vector
                If the system is inconsistent, explain how you know it.
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    The solution is <m>\begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ 3 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Solve the following system of equations: 
                <md>
                    \begin{cases}
                        2x_1 + 4x_2 + 6x_3 = 0 \\
                        4x_1 + 5x_2 + 6x_3 = 0 \\
                        3x_1 + x_2 - 2x_3 = 0
                    \end{cases}
                </md>
                If the system is consistent, write the solution set as a linear combination of basic vectors. 
                If the system is inconsistent, explain how you know it. 
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    This one has only the trivial solution <m>\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0\end{bmatrix}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Solve the following system of equations: 
                <md>
                    \begin{cases}
                        x_1 + 2x_2 - x_3 = 0 \\
                        3x_1 - 3x_2 + 2x_3 = 0 \\
                        -x_1 - 11x_2 + 6x_3 = 0
                    \end{cases}
                </md>
                If the system is consistent, write the solution set as a linear combination of basic vectors. 
                If the system is inconsistent, explain how you know it.
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    The solutions are of the form <m>t\begin{bmatrix} -\frac{1}{9} \\ \frac{5}{9} \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, where <m>t</m> is an arbitrary constant.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        
        <exercise>
            <p>
                Solve the following system of equations: 
                <md>
                    \begin{cases}
                        3x + 3y + 2w = 0 \\
                        y - z = 0 \\
                        3x + 5y - 2z + 2w = 0
                    \end{cases}
                </md>
                If the system is consistent, write the solution set as a linear combination of basic vectors. 
                If the system is inconsistent, explain how you know it. 
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    The solutions are of the form <m>z\begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \\ 0\end{bmatrix} + w\begin{bmatrix}-\frac{2}{3} \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, where <m>z</m> and <m>w</m> are arbitrary constants.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercisegroup>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                Given the following matrix equivalent to some coefficient matrix <m>A</m>, describe all solutions of <m>A\v{x}= \v{0}</m> in parametric vector form. 
                </p>
            </introduction>
            <exercise>
                <md>
                    \begin{bmatrix} 
                    1 \amp 3 \amp -3 \amp 7 \\ 
                    0 \amp 1 \amp -4 \amp 5 
                    \end{bmatrix}
                </md>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        The solution set in parametric vector form is 
                        <m>\mathbf{x} = s \begin{bmatrix} -9 \\ 4 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + t\begin{bmatrix} 8 \\ -5 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, where <m>s</m> and <m>t</m> are arbitrary constants.
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>

            <exercise>
                <md>
                    \begin{bmatrix} 
                    3 \amp -9 \amp 6 \\ 
                    -1 \amp 3 \amp -2 
                    \end{bmatrix}
                </md>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        The solution set in parametric vector form is 
                        <m>\mathbf{x} = s \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + t \begin{bmatrix} -2 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, where <m>s</m> and <m>t</m> are arbitrary constants.
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>

            <exercise>
                <md>
                    \begin{bmatrix} 
                    1 \amp -4 \amp -2 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp -5 \\ 
                    0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\ 
                    0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -4 \\ 
                    0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 
                    \end{bmatrix}
                </md>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        The solution set in parametric vector form is 
                        <m>\mathbf{x} = s \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + t \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + u \begin{bmatrix} -5 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 4 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, where <m>s</m>, <m>t</m>, and <m>u</m> are arbitrary constants.
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
        </exercisegroup>
    </worksheet>

    <worksheet xml:id="ws-MidtermReview-RowEchelonForm">
        <title>(Reduced) Row Echelon Form</title>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Row reduce the following matrix to reduced row echelon form. 
                Circle the pivot positions (aka the leading <m>1</m>s) in the final matrix and in the original matrix, and list the pivot columns (aka columns that contain a leading <m>1</m>). 
                <md>
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                    1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\
                    4 \amp 5 \amp 6 \amp 7 \\
                    6 \amp 7 \amp 8 \amp 9
                    \end{bmatrix}
                </md>
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    The reduced row echelon form is 
                    <m>
                        \begin{bmatrix}
                        1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp -2 \\
                        0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
                        0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0
                        \end{bmatrix}
                    </m>.
                    The pivot positions are at <m>(1,1)</m> and <m>(2,2)</m> entries. 
                    The pivot columns are Column 1 and Column 2.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercisegroup>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                In the following exercises, find the solutions of the systems whose augmented matrices are given. 
                </p>
            </introduction>

            <exercise>
                <md>
                \begin{bmatrix}
                    0 \amp 1 \amp -6 \amp \mid \amp 5 \\
                    1 \amp -2 \amp 7 \amp \mid \amp -4
                \end{bmatrix}
                </md>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        The solution in parametric form is 
                        <m>\mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix} 6 \\ 5 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + t \begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ 6 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, where <m>t</m> is an arbitrary constant.
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>

            <exercise>
                <md>
                \begin{bmatrix}
                    3 \amp -4 \amp 2 \amp \mid \amp 0 \\
                    -9 \amp 12 \amp -6 \amp \mid \amp 0 \\
                    -6 \amp 8 \amp -4 \amp \mid \amp 0
                \end{bmatrix}
                </md>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        The solution in parametric form is 
                        <m>\mathbf{x} = s \begin{bmatrix} \frac{4}{3} \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + t \begin{bmatrix} -\frac{2}{3} \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, where <m>s</m> and <m>t</m> are arbitrary constants.
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>

            <exercise>
                <md>
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                    1 \amp -3 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 0 \amp \mid \amp -2 \\
                    0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -4 \amp \mid \amp 1 \\
                    0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 9 \amp \mid \amp -4 \\
                    0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \mid \amp 0
                \end{bmatrix}
                </md>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        The solution in parametric vector form is 
                        <m>\mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix} -3 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ -4 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + s \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + t \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \\ 0 \\ -9 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, where <m>s</m> and <m>t</m> are arbitrary constants.
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
        </exercisegroup>
    </worksheet>

    <worksheet xml:id="ws-MidtermReview-TypesEquations">
        <title>Vector Equations and Matrix Equation</title>
        
        <exercise>
            <p>
                Solve the following vector equation: 
            </p>
            <me>
                x_1 \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix} + 
                x_2 \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix} + 
                x_3 \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix} + 
                x_4 \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix} = 
                \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1 \\ -5 \end{bmatrix}
            </me>
            <p>
                If the system is consistent, write the solution set as a linear combination of the basis vectors. 
                If the system is inconsistent, explain how you know it. 
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>\v{x} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \\ -2 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + t \begin{bmatrix} -2 \\ 1 \\ -1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Solve the following matrix equation: 
            </p>
            <me>
                \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\ 1 \amp 3 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix} \v{x} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \\ 10 \end{bmatrix}
            </me>
            <p>
                If the system is consistent, write the solution set as a linear combination of the basis vectors. 
                If the system is inconsistent, explain how you know it. 
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    The system is inconsistent. 
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </worksheet>

    <worksheet xml:id="ws-MidtermReview-LinearIndependence">
        <title>Linear Independence</title>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>\set{\v{v}_1, \v{v}_2, \v{v}_3}</m> be a set of vectors in <m>\R^3</m> such that
            </p>
            <me>
                \v{v}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} \quad , \quad
                \v{v}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix} \quad , \quad 
                \v{v}_3 = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ -1 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix}
            </me>
            <p>
                Is this set of vectors linearly independent? Remember to justify your conclusion.
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    No
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>\set{\v{v}_1, \v{v}_2, \v{v}_3}</m> be a set of vectors in <m>\R^4</m> such that
            </p>
            <me>
                \v{v}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 0 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix} \quad , \quad
                \v{v}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} \quad , \quad 
                \v{v}_3 = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 0 \\ -1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}
            </me>
            <p>
                Is this set of vectors linearly independent? Remember to justify your conclusion.
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    Yes
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>\set{\v{v}_1, \v{v}_2, \v{v}_3, \v{v}_4}</m> be a set of vectors in <m>\R^4</m> such that
            </p>
            <me>
                \v{v}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} \quad , \quad
                \v{v}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} \quad , \quad 
                \v{v}_3 = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} \quad , \quad
                \v{v}_4 = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \\ -1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}
            </me>
            <p>
                Is this set of vectors linearly independent? 
                If not, find the <em>smallest</em> set that spans the same plane. 
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    No. 
                </p>

                <p>
                    The smallest set is <m>\set{\v{v}_1, \v{v}_2}</m>. 
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </worksheet>

    <worksheet xml:id="ws-MidtermReview-LinearTransformations">
        <title>Linear Transformations</title>
        
        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>T: \R^4 \to \R^3</m> be a linear transformation defined by <m>T(\v{x}) = A\v{x}</m>, where
                <md>
                    A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -4 \amp 7 \amp -5 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -4 \amp 3 \\ 2 \amp -6 \amp 6 \amp -4 \end{bmatrix}
                </md>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the value of <m>T\lp \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 3 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix} \rp</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Is <m>\v{b} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -5 \\ 7 \end{bmatrix}</m> an image of this linear transformation? 
                            Justify your reasoning. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>T\lp \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 3 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix} 32 \\ -18 \\ 28 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                No it is not. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>T: \R^3 \to \R^4</m> be a linear transformation defined by <m>T(\v{x}) = A\v{x}</m>, where
                <md>
                    A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\ 2 \amp 3 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
                </md>
                Is <m>\v{b} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 5 \\ -1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}</m> an image of this transformation? 
                Justify your reasoning. 
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    Yes, since <m>T\lp \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 5 \\ -1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>T: \R^4 \to \R^3</m> be a linear transformation such that
                <md>
                    T\lp \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}
                    \qquad \text{ and } \qquad
                    T\lp \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ -1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
                </md>
                Find <m>T\lp \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \\ -2 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix} \rp</m>
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>T\lp \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \\ -2 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix} -8 \\ 3 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>T: \R^3 \to \R^2</m> be a linear transformation such that
                <md>
                    T \lp \begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ -3 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix}2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
                    \, , \quad
                    T \lp \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix}0 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix}
                    \, , \, \text{ and } \quad
                    T \lp \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 3 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix}1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}
                </md>
                Find a matrix <m>A</m> such that <m>T</m> is defined by the formula <m>T(\v{x}) = A\v{x}</m>
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} -2 \amp -4 \amp 19 \\ -7 \amp -12 \amp 59 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Suppose <m>T:\R^2 \to \R^2</m> is a linear transformation such that <m>T</m> is a rotation by <m>\dfrac{11\pi}{2}</m> counterclockwise. 
                Find the standard matrix <m>A</m> that defines this transformation. 
                That is, find the matrix <m>A</m> such that <m>T(\v{x}) = A\v{x}</m>. 
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Suppose <m>T:\R^2 \to \R^2</m> is a linear transformation such that <m>T</m> is a reflection across the line by <m>y = 3x</m>. 
                Find the standard matrix <m>A</m> that defines this transformation. 
                That is, find the matrix <m>A</m> such that <m>T(\v{x}) = A\v{x}</m>. 
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} -\frac{4}{5} \amp \frac{3}{5} \\ \frac{3}{5} \amp \frac{4}{5} \end{bmatrix}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </worksheet>

    <worksheet xml:id="ws-MidtermReview-MatrixOperations">
        <title>Matrix Operations</title>
        
        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \\ 2 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
                Compute <m>\lp A^T A\rp^2</m>
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>\lp A^T A\rp^2 = \begin{bmatrix} 40 \amp 32 \\ 32 \amp 104 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp -1\end{bmatrix}</m>, <m>B = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}</m>, <m>C = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \\ 2 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>, <m>D = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \\ -1 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}</m>, and <m>E = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
                Compute the following if possible, and if not possible, explain why. 
                <ol marker="a. ">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>3A - 2B</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>5C</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>3E^T</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>B + D</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>4A^T - 3C</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>(A + C)^T</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>2B- 3E</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>A - D</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>(B - 2E)^T</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a. ">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Impossible. <m>A</m> is <m>2 \times 2</m> and <m>B</m> is <m>2 \times 3</m>; addition/subtraction requires identical dimensions.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\begin{bmatrix} 15 \amp -5 \\ 10 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 3 \\ 3 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Impossible. <m>B</m> is <m>2 \times 3</m> and <m>D</m> is <m>3 \times 2</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 3 \\ -2 \amp -4 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp -1 \amp 8 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Impossible. <m>A</m> is <m>2 \times 2</m> and <m>D</m> is <m>3 \times 2</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ -1 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Compute the following matrix-vector products: 
                <ol marker="a. ">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\begin{bmatrix} -4 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 6 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 7 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\begin{bmatrix} 6 \amp 5 \\ -4 \amp -3 \\ 7 \amp 6 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a. ">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Impossible. The number of columns in the matrix (2) does not match the number of entries in the vector (3).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\begin{bmatrix} -9 \\ 5 \\ -11 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        
        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ 5 \amp -8 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp 3\end{bmatrix}</m>, <m>B = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ 5 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}</m>, and <m>\v{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
                Compute 
                <ol marker="a. ">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>AB</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>BA</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>A\v{v}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>B\v{v}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a. ">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>AB = \begin{bmatrix} 8 \amp 8 \amp 6 \\ -44 \amp 12 \amp -2 \\ 12 \amp 8 \amp 6 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>BA = \begin{bmatrix} 8 \amp -16 \amp 4 \\ 16 \amp 12 \amp 8 \\ 14 \amp -12 \amp 6 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>A\v{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 21 \\ 9 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>B\v{v} = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 13 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ -1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>, <m>B = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -2 \\ \frac{1}{2} \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>, and <m>C = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 0 \\ 2 \amp 5 \\ 0 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
                Compute the following if possible, and if not possible, explain why.
                <ol marker="a. ">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>A^2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>AB</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>AC</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a. ">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Impossible. <m>A</m> is not a square matrix (<m>2 \times 3</m>), so it cannot be multiplied by itself.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Impossible. The number of columns in <m>A</m> (3) does not match the number of rows in <m>B</m> (2).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>AC = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 19 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </worksheet>

    <worksheet xml:id="ws-MidtermReview-Inverses">
        <title>Inverses of Matrices (and Related Stuff)</title>
        
        <exercise>
            <p>
                Find the inverse of the following matrix if possible. 
                If not possible, explain why.  
                <ol marker="a. ">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp -2 \\ -9 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>B = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp -4 \\ -1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>C = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 5 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>D = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -7 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a.">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>A^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ \frac{9}{2} \amp \frac{5}{2} \end{bmatrix}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>B</m> is not invertible. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>B</m> is not invertible. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>D^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 7 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 5 \amp 12 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\v{b} = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
                Solve the equation <m>A\v{x} = \v{b}</m> using <m>A^{-1}</m>. 
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>\v{x} = \begin{bmatrix} -9 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Find the inverse of the following matrix if possible. 
                If not possible, explain why.  
                <ol marker="a.">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 4 \amp -2 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 3 \amp 1 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>B = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \\ -3 \amp 1 \amp 4 \\ 2 \amp -3 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>C = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ -1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 4 \amp 5 \amp 9 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <answer>
                <ol marker="a.">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>A</m> is not invertible. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>B^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} 8 \amp 3 \amp 1 \\ 10 \amp 4 \amp 1 \\ \frac{7}{2} \amp \frac{3}{2} \amp \frac{1}{2} \end{bmatrix}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>C</m> is not invertible. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 3 \\ 1 \amp -1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\ 3 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
                Answer the following questions. 
                Remember to justify your conclusions.
            </p>
            
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>What is the size of <m>A</m>?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>How many pivot positions does <m>A</m> have?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>How many solution does the homogeneous equation <m>A\v{x} = \v{0}</m> have?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Is the matrix equation <m>A\v{x} = \v{b}</m> <em>always</em> consistent for all <m>\v{b} \in \R^4</m>?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Do the columns of <m>A</m> span <m>\R^4</m>?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Are the columns of <m>A</m> linearly independent?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Is <m>A</m> invertible?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Is <m>T: \R^4 \to \R^4</m> defined by <m>T(\v{x}) = A\v{x}</m> an injection?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Is <m>T: \R^4 \to \R^4</m> defined by <m>T(\v{x}) = A\v{x}</m> a surjection?</p>
                </li>
            </ol>

            <answer>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>4 \times 4</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>4</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Exactly one solution (the trivial solution). 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Yes
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Yes
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Yes
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Yes
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Yes
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Yes
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>B = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
                Answer the following questions. Remember to justify your conclusions.
            </p>
            
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>What is the size of <m>B</m>?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>How many pivot positions does <m>A</m> have?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>How many solution does the homogeneous equation <m>B\v{x} = \v{0}</m> have?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Is the matrix equation <m>B\v{x} = \v{b}</m> <em>always</em> consistent for all <m>\v{b} \in \R^3</m>?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Do the columns of <m>B</m> span <m>\R^3</m>?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Are the columns of <m>B</m> linearly independent?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Is <m>A</m> invertible?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Is <m>T: \R^3 \to \R^3</m> defined by <m>T(\v{x}) = B\v{x}</m> an injection?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Is <m>T: \R^3 \to \R^3</m> defined by <m>T(\v{x}) = B\v{x}</m> a surjection?</p>
                </li>
            </ol>

            <answer>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>3 \times 3</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>3</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Exactly one solution (the trivial solution). 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Yes
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Yes
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Yes
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Yes
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Yes
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Yes
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>C = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 3 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
                Answer the following questions. Remember to justify your conclusions.
            </p>
            
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>What is the size of <m>C</m>?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>How many pivot positions does <m>C</m> have?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>How many solution does the homogeneous equation <m>C\v{x} = \v{0}</m> have?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Is the matrix equation <m>C\v{x} = \v{b}</m> <em>always</em> consistent for all <m>\v{b} \in \R^5</m>?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Do the columns of <m>C</m> span <m>\R^5</m>?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Are the columns of <m>C</m> linearly independent?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Is <m>C</m> invertible?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Is <m>T: \R^5 \to \R^5</m> defined by <m>T(\v{x}) = C\v{x}</m> an injection?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Is <m>T: \R^5 \to \R^5</m> defined by <m>T(\v{x}) = C\v{x}</m> a surjection?</p>
                </li>
            </ol>

            <answer>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>5 \times 5</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>4</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Infinitely many solutions. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            No
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            No
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            No
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            No
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            No
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            No
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </worksheet>

